{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564117"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:10:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:10:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16942"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16942"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.34,0.01,0.03,0.55]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9632"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108985"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9632"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16942"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91355"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1022"},{"type":"tags","id":"2451"},{"type":"tags","id":"2585"},{"type":"tags","id":"4507"},{"type":"tags","id":"4531"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22718"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35740"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35743"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35744"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40662"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108985"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to a rural hospital at 31 weeks gestation with a two-hour history of regular uterine contractions occurring every five minutes. This is her first pregnancy and she has had an uncomplicated antenatal course. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 118/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft with a gravid uterus and regular contractions are palpable. The cardiotocograph shows regular contractions and normal fetal heart rate patterns. The cervix is 1 cm dilated on speculum examination. There is no evidence of ruptured membranes. Fetal fibronectin testing is positive. The nearest tertiary centre with neonatal intensive care facilities is two hours away by road.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Observation for 24 hours in rural centre with tocolysis and steroids","Transfer to tertiary centre after giving tocolysis, steroids and oral antibiotics","Observation for 24 hours in rural centre","Transfer to tertiary centre","Transfer to tertiary centre after giving tocolysis and steroids"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with threatened preterm labour at 31 weeks gestation with a positive fetal fibronectin test, indicating an increased risk of delivery within 7-14 days. The presence of regular contractions and cervical dilatation, combined with the positive fetal fibronectin, suggests this is possible preterm labour rather than false labour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to tertiary centre after giving tocolysis and steroids\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. Tocolysis can delay delivery by 48 hours, allowing time for steroid administration to enhance fetal lung maturity and safe transfer to a facility with appropriate neonatal care capabilities. Betamethasone or dexamethasone should be administered prior to transfer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntibiotics are recommended for patients with established preterm labour, patients with preterm pre labour rupture of membranes and in patients with known or suspected chorioamnionitis. In this case, the patient does not have ruptured membranes AND is not in active/established labour (\u0026gt;4cm dilated) and therefore no \u003Cstrong\u003Eantibiotic\u003C/strong\u003E therapy is indicated. Of interest, the positive predictive value of fetal fibronectin is quite low (~20%) so it is very possible that this patient may not go on to established pre-term labour. If this patient did rupture her membranes or progress to active labour then antimicrobial prophylaxis would be recommended. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation for 24 hours in rural centre with tocolysis and steroids\u003C/strong\u003E would delay appropriate care and risk delivery in a facility without adequate neonatal support. While the medications are appropriate, the location is not.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation for 24 hours in rural centre\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the high risk of progression to delivery based on the positive fetal fibronectin and clinical findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to tertiary centre\u003C/strong\u003E without prior medications misses the opportunity to improve neonatal outcomes through antenatal steroids and risks delivery en route without the benefit of these interventions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Women with threatened preterm labour should be transferred to a facility with appropriate neonatal care capabilities when safe and feasible.","Antenatal corticosteroids significantly improve neonatal outcomes when given between 23-34 weeks gestation.","Tocolysis can delay delivery by 48 hours to allow for steroid administration and transfer to an appropriate facility.","Antibiotics for GBS prophylaxis are reserved for cases where membranes are ruptured or a patient is intrapartum/in active labour (\u003E4cm)"],"references":["Queensland Health. Guideline for premature rupture of membranes at term [Internet]. Brisbane: Queensland Health; 2021 [cited 2024 June 7]. Available from: https://www.health.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0019/140149/g-ptl.pdf","National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE). Preterm labour and birth [Internet]. London: NICE; 2015 [cited 2024 June 7]. Available from: https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng25"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91355"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16942"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91355"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-15T15:48:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-15T15:50:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9632"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108985"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt"